# Domain Object Encapsulation

Domain objects (entities, value objects, compounds, aggregates) **MUST** follow strict encapsulation principles with private readonly properties and controlled access through getters/setters.

## General Principle: Private Readonly Properties

**ALWAYS use `private readonly`** for properties in domain objects unless they need internal modification.

- **Value Objects**: All properties must be `private readonly`
- **Entities**: All properties must be `private readonly` (immutability)
- **Compounds**: All properties must be `private readonly`
- **Aggregates**: Root entity properties must be `private readonly`

## Property Visibility Rules

### ✅ CORRECT - Private Readonly Properties

```typescript
export class Category {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly name: Name,
    private readonly slug: Slug,
  ) {}

  getId(): Id {
    return this.id
  }

  getName(): Name {
    return this.name
  }

  getSlug(): Slug {
    return this.slug
  }
}

export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly title: Title,
    private readonly slug: Slug,
    private readonly description: Description,
    // ... all properties private readonly
  ) {}

  getId(): Id {
    return this.id
  }

  getTitle(): Title {
    return this.title
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Public Properties

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Public properties expose internal structure
export class Category {
  constructor(
    public readonly id: Id,        // ❌ NO - Should be private
    public readonly name: Name,     // ❌ NO - Should be private
    public readonly slug: Slug,    // ❌ NO - Should be private
  ) {}
}

// ❌ WRONG - Missing readonly for immutability
export class User {
  constructor(
    private id: Id,  // ❌ NO - Should be readonly for immutability
    private role: UserRole,
  ) {}
}
```

## Getters and Setters

### Access Through Getters

**NEVER** expose properties directly. **ALWAYS** provide getter methods to access internal state.

### ✅ CORRECT - Getter Methods

```typescript
export class City {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly name: CityName,
    private readonly slug: Slug,
    private readonly countryId: CountryId,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Public getter methods
  getId(): Id {
    return this.id
  }

  getName(): CityName {
    return this.name
  }

  getSlug(): Slug {
    return this.slug
  }

  getCountryId(): CountryId {
    return this.countryId
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Direct Property Access

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Direct property access
export class City {
  constructor(
    public readonly id: Id,  // ❌ NO - Direct access, no encapsulation
    public readonly name: CityName,
  ) {}

  // ❌ Wrong usage - accessing directly
  // Usage: city.id.toString() - Bypasses encapsulation
}

// ❌ WRONG - No getters
export class City {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly name: CityName,
  ) {}
  // ❌ NO - No getter methods, cannot access properties
}
```

## Setters with Validation

When properties need to be modified (rare in DDD), use setter methods **with validation**.

### ✅ CORRECT - Setters with Validation

```typescript
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private role: UserRole,  // ❗ Mutable when needed
    private readonly venueIds: Set<VenueId>,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Getter
  getRole(): UserRole {
    return this.role
  }

  // ✅ Setter with validation (when mutation is necessary)
  setRole(newRole: UserRole): void {
    if (!newRole) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Role cannot be null',
        400,
        'INVALID_ROLE',
      )
    }

    // Business rule: Validate role transition if needed
    if (this.role.isAdmin() && !newRole.isAdmin()) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Cannot downgrade admin role',
        400,
        'ROLE_DOWNGRADE_NOT_ALLOWED',
      )
    }

    this.role = newRole
  }

  // ✅ Method to add venue (mutating internal collection)
  addVenue(venueId: VenueId): void {
    if (!venueId) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Venue ID cannot be null',
        400,
        'INVALID_VENUE_ID',
      )
    }

    if (this.venueIds.has(venueId)) {
      return // Idempotent operation
    }

    this.venueIds.add(venueId)
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Immutable Modifications

For entities that should remain immutable, create new instances:

```typescript
export class Category {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly name: Name,
    private readonly slug: Slug,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Create new instance for modifications (immutability)
  withName(newName: Name): Category {
    return new Category(this.id, newName, this.slug)
  }

  withSlug(newSlug: Slug): Category {
    return new Category(this.id, this.name, newSlug)
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Public Setters Without Validation

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Public property allows direct mutation
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    public role: UserRole,  // ❌ NO - Direct mutation without validation
  ) {}
}

// ❌ WRONG - Setter without validation
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private role: UserRole,
  ) {}

  // ❌ NO - No validation, no business rules
  setRole(role: UserRole): void {
    this.role = role
  }
}
```

## Value Object Encapsulation

Value objects **MUST** have all properties `private readonly`:

### ✅ CORRECT - Value Object Encapsulation

```typescript
export class Name {
  private constructor(private readonly value: string) {}

  static create(value: string): Name {
    if (!value || value.trim().length === 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Name cannot be empty', 400)
    }
    return new Name(value.trim())
  }

  // ✅ Getter with controlled access
  toString(): string {
    return this.value
  }

  getValue(): string {
    return this.value
  }

  equals(other: Name): boolean {
    return this.value === other.value
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Public Value Object Properties

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Public property in value object
export class Name {
  constructor(
    public readonly value: string,  // ❌ NO - Should be private
  ) {}
}
```

## Compound Objects Encapsulation

Compound objects that combine multiple entities follow the same rules:

### ✅ CORRECT - Compound Object Encapsulation

```typescript
export class PostWithProfile {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly externalId: ExternalId,
    private readonly username: Username,
    private readonly profile: Profile,  // Nested entity, also encapsulated
    private readonly caption: Caption,
    // ... other properties private readonly
  ) {}

  // ✅ Getters for access
  getId(): Id {
    return this.id
  }

  getProfile(): Profile {
    return this.profile
  }

  getUsername(): Username {
    return this.username
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Public Properties in Compounds

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Public properties in compound
export class PostWithProfile {
  constructor(
    public readonly id: Id,  // ❌ NO - Should be private
    public readonly profile: Profile,  // ❌ NO - Should be private
  ) {}
}
```

## Exceptions: Internal Modification

Properties that need internal modification (collections, counters, etc.) should still be `private` but may not be `readonly`:

### ✅ CORRECT - Internal Mutable Collections

```typescript
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: Id,
    private readonly role: UserRole,
    private venueIds: Set<VenueId>,  // ❗ Not readonly - needs mutation
  ) {}

  // ✅ Controlled mutation through method
  addVenue(venueId: VenueId): void {
    if (!venueId) {
      throw new OneJsError('Venue ID required', 400)
    }
    this.venueIds.add(venueId)
  }

  // ✅ Getter returns copy for immutability
  getVenueIds(): ReadonlySet<VenueId> {
    return new Set(this.venueIds)
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Protected Properties for Inheritance

When using inheritance, protected properties may be used:

```typescript
export class Event {
  constructor(
    protected readonly id: Id,  // ✅ Protected for inheritance
    protected readonly title: Title,
    // ...
  ) {}
}

export class SpecialEvent extends Event {
  constructor(
    id: Id,
    title: Title,
    private readonly specialProperty: SpecialProperty,
  ) {
    super(id, title, /* ... */)
    // Can access protected properties from base class
  }
}
```

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- Use `private readonly` for all properties in domain objects
- Provide getter methods for property access: `getId()`, `getName()`, etc.
- Use setter methods with validation when mutation is necessary
- Keep value objects fully immutable with `private readonly` properties
- Use controlled methods for mutating internal collections
- Return copies of mutable collections from getters: `ReadonlySet<T>`, `readonly T[]`
- Use `protected readonly` only when inheritance requires it

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't use `public readonly` properties - always use getters
- Don't expose properties directly without getters
- Don't make properties mutable without validation
- Don't create setters without business rule validation
- Don't return mutable collections directly from getters
- Don't skip encapsulation "for convenience"
- Don't use public properties even if they're readonly

